Package com.rb.nonbiz.collections

Class DetailedPartitionModification<K>

java.lang.Object
com.rb.nonbiz.collections.DetailedPartitionModification<K>
public class DetailedPartitionModification<K>
extends java.lang.Object
This is a set of changes that can be applied to a Partition to result in a new partition. The semantics of how these can be applied to the original partition (call it P) are as follows:
  • getKeysToAdd() : assert these don't exist in the original partition; use the new weights.
  • getKeysToIncrease(): assert these exist in the original partition; add the supplied weights to the existing ones.
  • getKeysToRemove() : assert these exist in the original partition with a weight equal to the supplied one (subject to getEpsilonForRemovalSanityChecks() ); these keys will not appear in the modified partition.
  • getKeysToDecrease() : assert these exist in the original partition; subtract the supplied weights from the existing ones.

See the getters for explanations on the epsilons. They are not the same, intentionally. If, for example, each individual item to be removed has precision in the single bps (e.g. due to rounding), i.e. it is imprecise to 0.5 bps, then it's possible that many such < 0.5 bps deviations (assuming they don't cancel out) add up to much more than 1 bps, in which case getEpsilonForNetAdditionSanityCheck() should be larger than getEpsilonForRemovalSanityChecks().

    • getKeysToRemove

      public RBMap<K,​UnitFraction> getKeysToRemove()
      Items to remove, together with their existing weights, which will be used for sanity checking purposes.

      This could have been a plain RBSet, since the original / existing weights aren't really needed for determining the final partition. However, specifying the existing weights is useful for having construction preconditions that confirm that the total additions add up to the same percentage as deletions. Also, in scenarios where this is used in tests to convey expected behavior, specifying the existing weights will add extra clarity to the tests.

    • getEpsilonForNetAdditionSanityCheck

      public java.util.Optional<UnitFraction> getEpsilonForNetAdditionSanityCheck()
      There is a precondition that the total fractions to add or increase must equal the total fractions to subtract or increase. This makes sense, so that the total of everything still remains at 100%. However, in some cases such as tests (where we want to avoid too much precision because it clutters up the test results), the difference may be larger than the usual epsilon of 1e-8. In such cases, getEpsilonForNetAdditionSanityCheck() allow us to specify a larger (and possibly also smaller) epsilon. The reason it is optional is that if it is present, then the SingleDetailedPartitionModificationApplier will know about it so that it can normalize the weights to add up to exactly 100%.
